The t-distribution

Mike Hitchman

10/20/2021

The Scene

The central limit theorem for means says that if we draw an independent sample of size \(n\) from a distribution that has population mean \(\mu\) and standard deviation \(\sigma\) then, assuming \(n\) is sufficiently large, the distribution for \(\bar{x}\) is approximately normal with mean = \(\mu\) and standard deviation = \(\sigma/\sqrt{n}\). That is, \[ \bar{x} \sim N\left(\mu,\frac{\sigma}{\sqrt{n}}\right).\]

This means that if we gather a random sample of size \(n\) and compute the sample mean \(\bar{x}\), the test statistic \[z = \frac{\bar{x}-\mu}{\sigma/\sqrt{n}}\] lives in a standard normal distribution \(N(0,1)\).
Knowing this, we can make reasoned arguments about the value of an unknown population mean based on analysis of a sample mean \(\bar{x}\). For instance, a 95% confidence interval for \(\mu\) based on a sample mean \(\bar{x}\) is given by: \[\bar{x} \pm 1.96 \cdot \frac{\sigma}{\sqrt{n}}.\]

But theres one big catch. Computing the \(z\) statistic or finding the confidence interval requires us to know the value of the population standard deviation \(\sigma\). What if we dont know \(\sigma\)?

This is a fair, important question because, in practice, we rarely know \(\sigma\).

Our workaround is this: When we gather an independent sample, we use \(s\), the sample standard deviation, as an estimate for \(\sigma\).

There is a measurable cost to using this approximation, however, because there will be variation from sample to sample in the value of \(s\). The goal of this page is to account for this cost.

If we replace \(\sigma\) with \(s\), we call the revised statistic a t statistic: \[t = \frac{\bar{x}-\mu}{s/\sqrt{n}}.\] The t statistic does not live in a standard normal distribution. The distribution of this statistic is more like a bell-curve with fatter tails. The actual model for this type of distribution is called a t-distribution.

There is actually an entire, infinite family of t-distributions, one for each positive integer. We refer to a particular t-distribution by this integer, which by convention is called the degrees of freedom.

Below are plots for t-distributions with 2, 8, and 20 degrees of freedom, which we denote as \(t_2, t_8, t_{20}\). For comparison, the plot also contains the standard normal distribution \(N(0,1)\).

We remark that the larger the degrees of freedom number (df) gets, the closer the distribution \(t_{\text{df}}\) gets to \(N(0,1)\).

Comparing z-scores and t-scores

Lets take a minute to dive into the difference between t-scores and z-scores.

The code below makes many repetitions (20,000) of the following process:

  1. Draw a sample of size \(n=5\) from \(N(10,2)\), a normal distribution with mean \(\mu = 10\) and standard deviation \(\sigma = 2\).

  2. Record the sample mean \(\bar{x}\) and sample standard deviation \(s\) of this sample.

  3. Determines the z statistic \[z = \frac{\bar{x}-10}{2/\sqrt{5}}.\]

  4. Determine the t statistic \[t = \frac{\bar{x}-10}{s/\sqrt{5}}.\]

The code also records the 20,000 \(z\)-scores and the 20,000 \(t\)-scores in the vectors z_scores and t_scores, respectively.

trials<-20000
n=5
z_scores=c()
t_scores=c()
for (i in 1:trials){
  samp <- rnorm(n,mean=10,sd = 2)
  xbar <- mean(samp)
  s <- sd(samp)
  z <- (xbar-10)/(2/sqrt(n))
  t <- (xbar-10)/(s/sqrt(n))
  z_scores=c(z_scores,z)
  t_scores=c(t_scores,t)
  }

Below are histogram density plots of the z-scores and t-scores produced in the code above. The \(z\) scores live in a \(N(0,1)\) distribution, and the \(t\)-scores live in a \(t_4\) distribution. Notice the t-distribution has fatter tails.

We can also check the histogram of t-scores against the N(0,1) density curve, and against the \(t_4\) density curve. Which density curve is the better model?

Notes

  1. If the underlying distribution were drawing from is normal, as was the case in the simulation above, then the distribution for \(t=\frac{\bar{x}-\mu}{s/\sqrt{n}}\) is precisely a t-distribution, regardless of the sample size.

  2. If the underlying distribution were drawing from is NOT normal, as in the case below, the t-distribution is a reasonable model as long as the sample size is fairly large (usually at least 30) and no extreme values are present.

Drawing from a non-normal distribution

Suppose we are drawing from a skewed right population such as the one represented in the histogram below.

pop <- rchisq(50000,df=8)
hist(pop,breaks=30,main="A skewed right population",col="dodgerblue",xlab="value")

Lets take a sample of size \(n = 5\) from this population, determine \(\bar{x}\), \(s\), and then compute \[t = \frac{\bar{x}-\mu}{s/\sqrt{n}},\] where \(\mu\) = mean(pop)=7.9803691. Then we repeat this 10,000 times and plot the 10,000 t-scores.

trials<-10000
mu = mean(pop)
n = 5
t_scores=c()
for (i in 1:trials){
  samp <- sample(pop,n)
  xbar <- mean(samp)
  s <- sd(samp)
  t <- (xbar-mu)/(s/sqrt(n))
 t_scores=c(t_scores,t)
  }

If we stack these t-scores into a histogram, is the \(t_4\) density curve a good fit?

# make a plot
tscore <- data.frame(t_scores)
p <- ggplot(tscore) +
  geom_histogram(aes(x = t_scores, y = ..density..),
                 binwidth = .2, fill = "grey", color = "black")
x <- seq(-6,6,.01)
y <- dt(x,n-1)
df<-data.frame(x,y)
p + geom_line(data = df, aes(x = x, y = y), color = "blue") + xlim(-6,6) +
  ggtitle(expression(paste("t-scores from samples of size 5, and a ", t[4]," curve")))

Not so snug. How about we repeat this game but with a larger sample size, say \(n = 30\):

trials<-10000
mu = mean(pop)
n = 30
t_scores=c()
for (i in 1:trials){
  samp <- sample(pop,n)
  xbar <- mean(samp)
  s <- sd(samp)
  t <- (xbar-mu)/(s/sqrt(n))
 t_scores=c(t_scores,t)
  }

# make a plot
tscore <- data.frame(t_scores)
p <- ggplot(tscore) +
  geom_histogram(aes(x = t_scores, y = ..density..),
                 binwidth = .2, fill = "grey", color = "black")
x <- seq(-6,6,.01)
y <- dt(x,n-1)
df<-data.frame(x,y)
p + geom_line(data = df, aes(x = x, y = y), color = "blue") + xlim(-6,6) +
  ggtitle(expression(paste("t-scores from samples of size 30, and a ", t[29]," curve")))

Better. How about larger still, say \(n = 100\)?

 t_scores=c(t_scores,t)
